  "analysis_markdown": "## Local Diff Analysis\n\nThis diff adds HTTP API server capabilities to the Factory CLI tool. A new `factory/server.py` module introduces a FastAPI application with a `/hello` endpoint, while the CLI gains a `serve` command that binds and starts the server via uvicorn. Port validation (0-65535) is enforced at the CLI level. Dependencies on fastapi>=0.100 and uvicorn>=0.23 are added as hard requirements; test dependencies (pytest, httpx) are optional. Comprehensive test coverage includes endpoint validation (response body, content-type, HTTP method handling) and CLI option parsing. This represents a significant architectural shift from pure CLI tool to hybrid CLI+server application.\n\n### Suggested Review Focus\n- Dependency Impact: FastAPI and uvicorn are now hard dependencies for all users, even those only using CLI. Consider whether these should be optional dependencies or if the tool's purpose justifies bundling them.\n- Error Handling & Resilience: uvicorn.run() has no try/catch wrapper. Port binding failures, socket errors, or Ctrl+C handling should be explicit and user-friendly.\n- Security & Defaults: Server defaults to 127.0.0.1 (localhost-only), which is safe. Verify this cannot be accidentally changed to 0.0.0.0 in production configs without explicit override.\n- Lazy Import Pattern: Server module is imported inside serve() function rather than at module level. Confirm this is intentional (e.g., to defer FastAPI initialization) vs. an oversight.\n- Test Coverage Gaps: test_serve_port_validation_valid_edge_cases is a stub (pass statement). Port 0 and 65535 should have actual validation or the test should be removed.\n\n### Trade-offs\n- Hard vs. optional dependencies: FastAPI/uvicorn bundled with all installs; increases package size and dependency surface for CLI-only users. Alternative: make them optional with conditional imports and clearer user messaging.\n- Validation location: Port range check is CLI-side; uvicorn may reject invalid ports differently at runtime. Duplication vs. single source of truth.\n- Endpoint minimalism: /hello is a placeholder; production features (health checks, versioning, metrics, auth) not yet present but will require expansion.\n- Default host binding: 127.0.0.1 is secure but limits external access; users must override explicitly. Verify no operational surprise.\n\n### Affected Modules\n- factory.cli — new `serve` command added to Typer app\n- factory.server — new module (FastAPI app instance and /hello endpoint)\n- pyproject.toml — dependency manifest updated\n- tests/ — new test package structure with two new test modules\n\n### Call Chain\n- factory serve --port 8000 → cli.serve() → uvicorn.run(factory.server.app, host='127.0.0.1', port=8000) → FastAPI middleware chain → /hello route handler → {'message': 'Hello, World!'}\n\n### Design Patterns\n- Separation of Concerns: HTTP logic isolated in factory/server.py; CLI orchestration in factory/cli.py\n- Lazy Module Loading: server module imported only when serve command executes (avoid import side-effects in non-server contexts)\n- Command Pattern: CLI commands as decorated methods with type-checked options\n- Test Fixture Pattern: pytest fixture for FastAPI TestClient reuse\n\n### Reviewer Checklist\n- Verify: Are fastapi and uvicorn required for all use cases, or should they be optional dependencies?\n- Verify: Does uvicorn.run() need timeout, shutdown signal handlers, or error wrapping?\n- Verify: Is the lazy import (inside function) intentional or should imports be at module level?\n- Test: Complete test_serve_port_validation_valid_edge_cases with actual port 0/65535 validation (not just pass)\n- Security: Confirm 127.0.0.1 default is documented and cannot be overridden via config file without explicit intent\n- Scope: Is /hello a placeholder, or is this the final minimal API? Clarify roadmap for versioning, health checks, auth\n- Documentation: CLI help text and docstrings present; confirm README/CLAUDE.md updated with usage examples\n- Integration: Do existing factory commands or downstream tools depend on import order or assume no server code loaded?\n",
